  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Real Estate Still Qualifies</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most common misconception in 2024-2026. Real estate investment was eliminated in October 2023. No property purchase—regardless of value, location, or type—qualifies for new Golden Visa applications. Existing holders can renew, but new applicants cannot use this route.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Total Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The €500,000 investment is just the beginning. Add €5,000+ per person in application fees, €5,000-15,000 in legal fees, €2,000-6,000/year in health insurance, and renewal fees every 2 years. A family of 4 should budget €50,000+ beyond the investment for the first 5 years.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting NHR Tax Benefits</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Non-Habitual Resident (NHR) tax regime—which offered 10 years of favorable tax treatment—is being phased out. New applicants after 2024 generally do not qualify. Do not structure your Golden Visa around NHR without confirming current eligibility with a Portuguese tax advisor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Travel Insurance Instead of Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Travel insurance does not satisfy the Golden Visa health insurance requirement. You need comprehensive private health insurance with no annual coverage limits. Applications with travel insurance will be rejected. Arrange proper coverage before applying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 7-Day Annual Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must spend at least 7 days in Portugal each year (or 14 days in each 2-year period). This sounds easy, but busy investors sometimes forget. Missing this requirement can jeopardize your renewal. Keep documentation of your stays.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Portugal -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Portugal</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Portugal has a well-regarded healthcare system, ranking 23rd globally on Numbeo's Health Care Index. As a Golden Visa holder, you'll have access to both private healthcare (via your mandatory insurance) and eventually the public system (SNS) once you establish residence.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Options for Golden Visa Holders</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare (Via Your Insurance)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>Immediate access from visa approval</li>
          <li>Short wait times for appointments</li>
          <li>Modern private hospitals (CUF, Lusíadas, Hospital da Luz)</li>
          <li>English-speaking doctors common</li>
          <li>Full choice of specialists</li>
          <li>Higher out-of-pocket if using local insurance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Public Healthcare (SNS)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>Available after registering as resident</li>
          <li>Free or low-cost for residents</li>
          <li>Good quality, especially in Lisbon/Porto</li>
          <li>Longer wait times for non-urgent care</li>
          <li>Less English availability</li>
          <li>Register at local Centro de Saúde</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Accessing Healthcare During Your 7 Days</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Since most Golden Visa holders spend only 7 days per year in Portugal, healthcare access looks different than for full-time residents:
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">For Routine Care</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your international health insurance covers you in your home country. Use Portuguese private hospitals if you need care during your 7-day visits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">For Emergencies in Portugal</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Go to any hospital emergency room (Urgência). Private hospitals like CUF have shorter waits. Your international insurance should cover emergency treatment. Keep insurance details handy.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">For Planned Procedures</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Some Golden Visa holders choose to time elective procedures with their Portugal visits, especially if Portuguese private healthcare offers good value. Coordinate with your insurer for pre-authorization.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Schengen healthcare:</strong> Your Portuguese residency gives you access to healthcare throughout the Schengen area under certain conditions. Your international insurance is essential for this—it covers you across Europe while your Portuguese status provides the legal right to treatment.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I still get a Golden Visa by buying property?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. As of October 2023, real estate investment no longer qualifies for new Golden Visa applications. This includes all property types—residential, commercial, urban, rural—regardless of value or location. Existing Golden Visa holders with property can continue to renew, but new applicants must use alternative investment routes (funds, capital transfer, job creation, or cultural contribution).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long do I actually need to spend in Portugal each year?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Just 7 days per year—or 14 days in each 2-year period. This is one of the most flexible residency requirements in Europe. The 7 days don't need to be consecutive. Your biometrics appointment and any AIMA visits count toward this requirement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family be included in my Golden Visa application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. You can include your spouse (or registered partner), dependent children (under 18, or older if financially dependent and studying), and dependent parents (yours and your spouse's). Each family member requires a separate application fee (€5,324.60 per person) and their own health insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get Portuguese citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You can apply for citizenship after 5 years of legal residency—one of the fastest paths in the EU. Requirements include: maintaining your investment throughout, passing a basic Portuguese language test (A2 level), clean criminal record, and demonstrating ties to Portugal. The 7-day annual presence requirement still applies during this period.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens to my investment after 5 years?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After obtaining permanent residence (5 years), you can divest your qualifying investment. For fund investments, this typically means waiting for the fund's natural exit or redemption period. You must maintain the investment during the entire Golden Visa period—withdrawing early can jeopardize your status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is health insurance really mandatory, or is it just recommended?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Mandatory. Your Golden Visa application will not be approved without proof of valid health insurance covering Portugal. Travel insurance is not accepted—you need comprehensive private health insurance with no annual coverage limits. You must maintain coverage throughout your residency and show valid insurance at each renewal.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

